{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280601652/1937113001/0060.xml":{"full_text":"TUNNEL OPENING\nNew Hudson Tube From\nWeehawken, N. J., to Be\nAvailable Dec. 22.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Nov. 30.\u2014Four thou\nsand years ago naked Assyrian slaves\ntoiled under a blazing tropical sun\nto build the world first river tunnel\u2014\nunder the muddy bed of the Euphrates.\n3.000 feet, from the royal palace of\nBabylon to the Temple of Jupiter.\nThen, for 40 centuries, river tun\nneling became a lost art.\nNot until 1842 did history again\nrecord the successful \"boring through\u201d\nof a river-bed tube\u2014the Thames River\nTunnel In England.\nThree weeks hence, on December\n22, another major engineering feat\nIn tunnel construction will be marked\nwith the opening of the first tube of\nManhattan's $75,000,000 two-way Lin\ncoln Tunnel from midtown New York\nto Weehawken, N. J.\nCost $42,000,000.\nBuilt at a cost of $42,000,000, the\ntube extends 8,215 feet from portal I\nto portal under the swirling tides of\nthe Hudson River.\nThe second tube will be completed\nlate In 1940 and will lie about 75\nfeet north of the first, thus permit\nting two-way \"solo\u201d traffic.\nFourteen workmen died in thrusting\nthe ring-shaped shell of the initial\ntube through the muck and silt of\nthe river bottom\u2014a job which began\nin March, 1934, and reached its dra\nmatic climax on August 22, 1935,\nwhen two huge steel cutting shields,\nboring from opposite sides of the river,\n\u201choled through\u201d and met within one\nquarter of an inch!\n\"Sandhogs\u201d Cheered Finish.\nHard-boiled \u201csandhogs.\" who risk\ndeath from the dread \"bends\" in their\neerie subterranean work chambers,\neheered at that marvel of engineering\nefficiency.\nThe mammoth tubes, sunk 75 feet\nbelow the river surface, packed in\n25 to 40 feet of ailt. will not He Inert.\nLake sluggish monsters of the deep,\nthey will actually \"writhe\u201d in their\nmuddy beds, rising and falling about\nan eighth of an inch with the daily\ntides, rising a quarter of an inch\nmore in summer and sinking the\nlame distance in winter.\nThe shell itself is 14 inches thick,\nmade of cast iron and cast steel, with\na diameter of 31 feet, reinforced by a\nlining of concrete. Iron and steel used\nin the whole project total 101,400 tons.\nFills Long-Standing Need.\nThe first tube, handling about 2,000\nvehicles an hour and something like\n7.500.000 a year, will fill a long-stand\ning need in bringing motorists into the\nmidtown heart of Manhattan instead\nof the southern extremity via the 10\nyear-old Holland Tunnel, or the north\nvia the George Washington Bridge.\nThe tube is \"air-conditioned\" by\n82 giant blowers, sleeping 150 tons\nof fresh air per minute through the I\nunseen ventilation ducts below the\nroadway. Among up-tc-the-minute\nInnovations is the roof of glittering\nglass tile\u2014a far cry from the rude\nmud-brick used by Assyrian slaves in\nthe Babylon Tunnel of 4,000 years ago.\n_ i\nBUSINESS UPTURN\nSEEN WITHIN YEAR\n\nCredit Men's Association Officer\nSays Labor-Capital Sanity\nNeeded.\n9j the Associated Press.\nDETROIT, Nov. 30.\u2014Henry H. Hei\nBiann, executive manager of the Na\ntional Association of Credit Men, pre\ndicted here yesterday a resumption of\nbusiness\u2019 \u201cforward movement\u201d in the\nearly fall of 1938.\nMr. Heimann. addressing the Eco\nnomic Club, said the \"greatest need\u201d\ncurrently is the \"return of sanity and\nfairness in capital-labor relationship.\u201d\nThe business outlook, he said, shaped\nup as:\n\u201cWith the exception of retail trade,\na generally continued decline in the\nnext few months, a possible continua\ntion of rather unsatisfactory volume\nthroughout the first six months of\n1938, and a resumption of the forward\nmovement In the early fall of \u201938.\u201d\nOIL TRIAL JUDGE TOLD\nCOMPETITION RESTORED\n\nDefense in Oil Price-Fixing Case\nContend Purchases in 1935 and\n1936 Re-Established System.\nBy the Associated Press.\nMADISON, Wis., Nov. 30.\u2014The de\nfense in the Government\u2019s gasoline\nprice-fixing case began yesterday its\nattempt to prove that major oil com\npany purchases of small refiners' gaso\nline in 1935 and 1936 restored a com\npetitive market.\nThe Government contends that the\nmajor companies bought gasoline as\npart of a scheme to raise and peg Mid\nwestern prices.\nThe jury, which had not been in\nthe courtroom since November 12,\nwhen arguments on dismissal motions\nbegan, was recalled yesterday when\nFederal Judge Patrick T. Stone with\nheld action on defense motions for ac\nquittal of the remaining 41 individ\nuals on trial. The court said the trial\ncould proceed without immediate de\ntermination of whether the individ\nuals should be dropped as defendants.\nTo Mark Star's Birthplace.\nPORT WAYNE, Inct, Nov. 30 UP).\u2014\nMayor Harry W. Baals said yesterday\nBelznick International Pictures, Inc.,\nplanned to place a bronze plaque at\na house here w'here Carole Lombard,\nfilm star, was bom October 6, 1908.\nThe mayor said Miss Lombard, born\nJane Alice Peters, would be Invited\nto attend the dedicatory ceremonies.\nA.E.F. Veteran Finally Returns\nTo Find Himself Enoch Arden\nBy the Associated Prees.\nSPRINGFIELD, 111., Nov. 30 Ai\nEnoch Arden of a long disbanded\narmy came back from war yesterdaj\nand found the bride, he left behind\nhad divorced him, remarried and wtu\nthe mother of a 17-year-old son bj\nher second husband.\nThe bewildered veteran, Halli<\nDaigh, 39 years old and forlornly foot\nloose since 1920, said he had heard\nnothing about his former wife sine*\nshortly after he bade her farewell al\nSan Antonio, Tex., 20 years ago to gc\nto France with the 7th Field Artillery\nWar made cruel and fantastic sporl\nof Hallie Daigh. He was reported\nmissing in action. Actually, he re\nlated, he passed the final year of the\nwar in a German prison camp, and\nwas in a hospital for seven or eight\nmonths after that. The effects ol\npoison gas, he said, weakened hii\nmemory for a few years after he wa*\nreleased from the hospital m 1920\nDaigh. in his own words, was in s\nfog:\n\u201cI was still suffering from the gas\nI guess. I reckon I just wandered\n\u2022round, not knowing particularly what\nI was doing.\u201d Complete recovery, he\nsaid, brought no solution of his prob\nlems; he didn\u2019t know which way to\nturn. He went on:\n\"I had been told indirectly that my\nparents were dead, so I thought I had\nno home ties, 1 didn't know what had\nhappened to my wife, but after all\nthose years I was afraid to interfere!\u201d\nThe caissons and guns, except in\nsleek and safe maneuvering, had long\nsince ceased to roll along, but Hallie\nDaigh continued to wander, to move\nup, closer perhaps, to the resolution\nof his strange, if obscure, destiny.\nA structural steel worker, he plied\nhis trade as he could. His wayward\ntravels brought him finally to Spring\nfield. Meeting an acquaintance from\nnearby Edinburg, where he and his\nformer wife lived of yore. Daigh\nlearned the other half of his story.\nBelieving him dead, his bride had ob\ntained a bill of divorcement and later\nremarried.\nSo Hallie Daigh CRlled upon her to\nmeet her husband, Otis Jennings, and\ntheir sturdy son. He also found his\nfather alive, now 75 years old. But\nit was true his mother was dead.\nThe future? Search Hallie. He'll\nhave to \u2018\u2018rise and shine,\u201d as he used\nto do back there in the days when\nthe caissons kept rolling along. \u201cI\u2019ll\nprobably pull out,\u201d he mused, rue\nfully, \"where to, I don't know. Just\nkeep on the move,. I guess.\u201d\nRAIDED CLUB REOPENS\n\nCounty Solicitor Clears Miami\nOperator After Hooded Visitatibn.\nMIAMI. Fla., Nov. 30 OP).\u2014County\nSolicitor Robert R. Taylor gave a\nclean bill of health to Club La Pa\nloma, reopening last night after hav\ning been closed once by hooded raid\ners and again by deputies sheriff.\nSolicitor Taylor said he could find\nno basts for charges against Pro\nprietor A1 Youst and 25 employes, ar\nrested Saturday night by Sheriff D. C.\nColeman, who said he would not let\nthe place reopen after the visit two\nweeks ago of 175 men and women\nin Ku Kiux Klan regalia.\nWOOER QUESTIONED\nIN LOVE SPAT BLAST\nSaid to Have Admitted Firing\nDynamite at Home of\nDivorcee.\nBy the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO, Nov. 30.\u2014Somewhat\nbanged up himself, Charles Karovich\nwas neld without formal charge for\nfurther questioning last night after\nhe had been accused of touching cfl a\ncouple of stick* of dynamite in con\nnection with his courtship of a young\ndivorcee.\nMrs. Patricia Davis, 21, on whose\nwindow sill the explosion occurred\nearly Sunday morning, was slightly in\njured. Seventeen windows were shat\ntered by the blast.\nKarovich had a black eye, received\nduring a struggle with police when\nthey arrested him at his home yester\nday. Assistant State's Attorney Mai\nCoglan said Karovich admitted he was\nthe dynamite wooer.\nAs the police got the story, there\nwas a spat between the couple Satur\nday night. Mrs. Davis went home.\nKarovich tried to get her on the tele\nphone three times, but failed. The\nexplosion followed.\nSONJA TAKEN HOME\nSkating Star to Be Examined for\nInjury on Set.\nHOLLYWOOD, Nov. 30 (*>).\u2014Sonja\nHenle, skating actress, left her studio\nand went home to bed yesterday be\ncause she felt dizzy.\nHer studio said she would be ex\namined today to determine if she\nhad suffered a slight brain concussion\nin a fall last Friday when one skate\nslipped on a piece of cotton.\nMANUFACTURER DIES\nELKHART, Ind., Nov. 30 OP).\u2014A\nheart attack caused the death here\nyesterday of Ferdinand A. Buescber,\n76, band instrument manufacturer.\nHe was president of the Art Musical\nInstnXinents, Inc., and founder of the\nBuescher Band Instrument Co.\nGood on specified trams only\u2014\n\u2022or details see flyers\u2014consult agents\nor Tolopfeno District 1424\nSu